The two decimal expressions with the over‑dots mean that the last digit in the decimal part is the one that repeats.

---

### 1.  Evaluate \(2.3\dot{7}\)

The number \(0.\dot{7}\) is the repeating decimal \(0.777\ldots = \frac{7}{9}\).

Hence

\[
2.3\dot{7}=2+0.3+\frac{0.\dot{7}}{10}=2+\frac{3}{10}+\frac{7}{90}
          =\frac{180+27+7}{90}
          =\frac{214}{90}
          =\frac{107}{45}\; .
\]

---

### 2.  Evaluate \(0.4\dot{5}\)

Similarly, \(0.4\dot{5}\) means \(0.4\) followed by an infinite string of \(5\)’s:

\[
0.4\dot{5}=0.4+\frac{0.\dot{5}}{10}= \frac{4}{10}+\frac{5}{90}
           =\frac{36+5}{90}
           =\frac{41}{90}\; .
\]

---

### 3.  Divide the two numbers

\[
\frac{2.3\dot{7}}{0.4\dot{5}}
  =\frac{\displaystyle\frac{107}{45}}
        {\displaystyle\frac{41}{90}}
  =\frac{107}{45}\times\frac{90}{41}
  =\frac{107\cdot 2}{41}
  =\frac{214}{41}
  \approx 5.2195121951\ldots
\]

---

The decimal expansion of \( \displaystyle\frac{214}{41}\) is

\[
5.219512195121951\ldots
\]

which truncates (or rounds) to **5.21951**.  
The only answer choice that matches this value is:

\[
